sitism as a mode of life, the common features of the wide range of organisms that adopt such a way of life, the reasons for parasites' extraordinary potential for continued adaptive radiation, and their role in molding community structure by means of their impact on the evolution of host species. In demonstrating the importance of parasitic interactions for determining population patterns and geographical distributions, Dr. Price generates further discussion and suggests new areas for research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aParasitesxEvolution. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Ecology.2bisacsh  aAdaptive radiation.  aAdelina tribolii.  aDactylogyrus.  aHeliconius.  aHymenolepis.  aSchistosoma.  aSpecies, packing.  achromosomal rearrangements.  acoevolution.  acoexistence.  adiversity of parasites.  aequilibrium.  aevolutionary rate.  aextinction probability.  agene flow.  agene-for-gene concept.  agenetic systems.  aimmune response.  ainbreeding.  amobility of parasites.  amutualism.  aoutbreeding.  apatchy resources.  apolymorphism.  apredators.  arare events.  aresources, ephemeral.  asurvivorship curves.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691209425423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691209425.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK